```

The moon icon shows when in dark mode (click to go light), sun icon shows when in light mode (click to go dark). Use a `.hidden` class to toggle visibility.

Add `<script src="js/theme.js"></script>` BEFORE confetti.js and game.js — ideally in the `<head>` with no `defer` to prevent flash of wrong theme. Actually, since this sets a data attribute on `<html>`, place it as early as possible. Put a small inline script in `<head>` that reads localStorage and sets the attribute immediately, then load `theme.js` at the bottom for the toggle logic.

Better approach for no-flash:
```html
<!-- In <head>, after CSS link -->
<script>
  (function() {
    var saved = localStorage.getItem('theme');
    if (saved) {
      document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', saved);
    } else if (window.matchMedia && window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: light)').matches) {
      document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', 'light');
    }
  })();
</script>
```

Then `js/theme.js` at the bottom handles the toggle button and icon state.

## js/theme.js

```javascript
(function() {
  'use strict';

  var THEME_KEY = 'theme';

  function getTheme() {
    return document.documentElement.getAttribute('data-theme') || 'dark';
  }

  function setTheme(theme) {
    document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', theme);
    localStorage.setItem(THEME_KEY, theme);
    updateToggleButton(theme);
  }

  function updateToggleButton(theme) {
    var toggle = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
    var sunIcon = document.getElementById('theme-icon-dark');
    var moonIcon = document.getElementById('theme-icon-light');
    if (!toggle || !sunIcon || !moonIcon) return;

    if (theme === 'light') {
      sunIcon.style.display = '';
      moonIcon.style.display = 'none';
      toggle.setAttribute('aria-label', 'Switch to dark mode');
    } else {
      sunIcon.style.display = 'none';
      moonIcon.style.display = '';
      toggle.setAttribute('aria-label', 'Switch to light mode');
    }
  }

  function init() {
    var currentTheme = getTheme();
    updateToggleButton(currentTheme);

    var toggle = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
    if (toggle) {
      toggle.addEventListener('click', function() {
        var newTheme = getTheme() === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark';
        setTheme(newTheme);
      });
    }

    // Listen for OS preference changes
    if (window.matchMedia) {
      window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').addEventListener('change', function(e) {
        if (!localStorage.getItem(THEME_KEY)) {
          setTheme(e.matches ? 'dark' : 'light');
        }
      });
    }
  }

  if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', init);
  } else {
    init();
  }
})();
```

## Conventions

- Match existing code style: IIFE pattern, `var` declarations, `'use strict'`
- No ES6+ syntax (existing code uses ES5)
- CSS: use the existing section comment pattern `/* ========== Section ========== */`
- No new dependencies
- Keep SVG icons inline (matching the existing help button pattern)

## Gotchas

- The `@keyframes rowComplete` uses a hardcoded `#52b788` — CSS custom properties work in keyframes in modern browsers but NOT in older ones. Use `var(--color-success)` — the browser support is fine for this app's target audience.
- The `.hidden` class uses `display: none` — use this for icon toggling or use inline `style.display`.
- The inline head script must NOT reference DOM elements (they don't exist yet) — it only sets `data-theme` on `documentElement`.
- The `prefers-color-scheme` check: default to dark if no preference and no saved value (the app was designed dark-first).
- Make sure `.btn-primary` text stays white in both themes (it's on a blue background).
